ray.rage.rendersystem

Interface RenderSystem

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Disposable
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    GL4RenderSystem

    public interface RenderSystem
extends Disposable
    A render system defines the functionality of a low-level 3D API.

    Low-level APIs, such as OpenGL or Vulkan, are meant to be thin abstraction layers between the platform and the actual graphics processing hardware. It is at this level that less abstracted concepts such as raw vertex geometry, data buffers, drawing surfaces, frame buffer swapping, view/projection matrices, coordinate system handedness, and display-modes become more relevant.

    The render system in this framework is intentionally decoupled from knowledge about the contents, organization, and structure of a scene, which are higher-level concepts delegated to the scene-manager. Rather, render systems take care of the "dirty work", i.e. lower-level details of how to deal with graphics hardware, GPU memory buffers, raw data storage, rendering-states, drawing surfaces, and shader-programs, among others.

    The key concept that bridges the gap between the scene-manager and low-level rendering, allowing both of them to be decoupled from each other, is the Renderable object. These are the objects that render-systems can process and, ultimately, draw on screen.

    Concrete implementations must have automatic back buffer swapping disabled by default. The decision of when to swap a back buffer is meant to be made at a higher-level. For example, this would allow a render-window with multiple viewports to have the contents of each viewport completely rendered before presenting the full result to the screen, rather than swapping the back buffers repeatedly for the partial results of each viewport during a single pass.

    Author:
    Raymond L. Rivera

      • swapBuffers

        void swapBuffers()
        Gets the render-system to swap the front and back buffers in order to display a completed scene.

        Drawing operations take place in an off-screen buffer, called the "back buffer", in order to avoid displaying scenes that are only partially drawn and other artifacts (e.g. flickering) to the viewer. See Multiple Buffering in Computer Graphics.

      • processRenderQueue

        void processRenderQueue(RenderQueue rq,
                        Matrix4 view,
                        Matrix4 proj)
        Submits the renderables in the given render-queue to the graphics pipeline so that they can be rendered on screen.
        Parameters:
        rq - The render-queue with the renderables to be rendered.
        view - The view matrix.
        proj - The projection matrix.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - If any of the arguments is null.
        java.lang.RuntimeException - If an unexpected problem arises during rendering. Note that these may be thrown from a separate thread, depending on implementation.

      • createGpuShaderProgram

        GpuShaderProgram createGpuShaderProgram(GpuShaderProgram.Type type)
        Creates a render-system-specific shader-program meant to be associated with a renderable.

        GPU shader-programs are required to render renderables. Any renderable submitted to the render-system without an associated shader-program will be logged and skipped.

        Parameters:
        type - type.
        Returns:
        A shader-program.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - If the name is empty.
        java.lang.RuntimeException - If the name has already been used.
